123
00:14:29.278 --> 00:14:32.978
releasing payload within the cell for cytotoxicity.

124
00:14:32.988 --> 00:14:36.958
That payload, in some cases, as with SG, is cell permeable

125
00:14:37.158 --> 00:14:40.708
and therefore can extrude to the microenvironment and

126
00:14:40.758 --> 00:14:44.038
kill neighboring cells, a so-called bystander effect for even

127
00:14:44.098 --> 00:14:46.498
target-negative neighboring cells.

128
00:14:46.538 --> 00:14:50.518
With an ADC with a relatively labile linker like SG, payload can be

129
00:14:50.558 --> 00:14:53.467
released even in the microenvironment without internalization,

130
00:14:54.438 --> 00:14:58.198
leading to a kind of outside bystander

131
00:14:58.478 --> 00:15:02.318
effect. So when we think about these mechanisms, there's data

132
00:15:02.618 --> 00:15:05.938
at each of these steps that's related to resistance.

133
00:15:06.358 --> 00:15:09.518
So obviously expression of the target can be important.

134
00:15:10.218 --> 00:15:14.058
Pathways for internalization and trafficking are showing up now when we look at

135
00:15:14.078 --> 00:15:18.018
resistance pathways. Lysosomal processing, a competent lysosome, for

136
00:15:18.038 --> 00:15:21.928
example, is important. Payload sensitivity and intrinsic sensitivity of

137
00:15:21.938 --> 00:15:24.978
the tumor cells and the bystander effect I talked about.

138
00:15:25.268 --> 00:15:29.258
And then what I'll come to at the end is findings from

139
00:15:30.038 --> 00:15:33.838
clinical trials that we're being able to unveil the immune microenvironment

140
00:15:33.878 --> 00:15:37.338
that's relevant to therapy and combinations.

141
00:15:39.098 --> 00:15:41.128
So if we think about first the target,

142
00:15:42.098 --> 00:15:45.878
particularly for the ADCs approved in breast cancer, which target either

143
00:15:45.918 --> 00:15:47.358
Trop-2 or HER2,

144
00:15:48.418 --> 00:15:51.838
target level has been only poorly predictive of

145
00:15:51.878 --> 00:15:55.718
response to these drugs. This is again the Phase III ASCENT

146
00:15:55.778 --> 00:15:59.758
trial where we're looking at progression-free survival by tertiles of Trop-2

147
00:15:59.798 --> 00:16:02.438
expression for the ADC versus chemotherapy.

148
00:16:02.878 --> 00:16:06.738
And what you see is there's only a rough correlation between Trop-2 expression

149
00:16:06.778 --> 00:16:10.458
and PFS on the ADC, but in each case, it's

150
00:16:10.498 --> 00:16:12.608
better than chemotherapy,

151
00:16:13.658 --> 00:16:17.538
and this is why we do not select based on expression for clinical

152
00:16:17.698 --> 00:16:19.838
use of SG.

153
00:16:21.938 --> 00:16:23.168
Now we wanted to look more

154
00:16:25.118 --> 00:16:28.938
broadly in patients at mechanisms of resistance, particularly in the

155
00:16:29.238 --> 00:16:33.217
acquired resistance setting. And so we study

156
00:16:33.227 --> 00:16:36.238
a group of patients who had been treated with advanced triple-negative breast

157
00:16:36.248 --> 00:16:40.218
cancer with SG as a single agent. And then a subset

158
00:16:40.238 --> 00:16:43.958
of patients who progressed went on to

159
00:16:44.338 --> 00:16:48.238
rapid autopsy ultimately, and we were able to do biopsies of multiple

160
00:16:48.438 --> 00:16:51.578
lesions, whole exome sequencing, and then look at

161
00:16:51.638 --> 00:16:55.498
pre-treatment versus post-treatment tumor changes and mechanisms of resistance in

162
00:16:55.538 --> 00:16:56.068
that setting.

163
00:16:56.958 --> 00:17:00.698
And what we found is that a number of lesions, all the

164
00:17:00.738 --> 00:17:04.648
lesions above the diaphragm harbored an acquired mutation in Trop-2,

165
00:17:04.679 --> 00:17:08.538
a missense mutation, and all the lesions below the diaphragm, in this case,

166
00:17:08.878 --> 00:17:12.018
harbored mutations in topoisomerase 1.

167
00:17:12.598 --> 00:17:16.518
This was immediately of interest because the Topo1 E418K mutation in

168
00:17:16.538 --> 00:17:19.979
particular was one that had never been seen in humans but was actually described

169
00:17:20.058 --> 00:17:23.528
many years ago in cell lines that were exposed to high levels of a Topo1 inhibitor,

170
00:17:23.838 --> 00:17:27.298
and you could actually elicit this mutation, which was proven to be a

171
00:17:27.318 --> 00:17:31.118
resistance mechanism. The Trop-2 mutation was

172
00:17:31.218 --> 00:17:34.378
novel, but we went on to show in this paper we published five years ago

173
00:17:34.998 --> 00:17:38.618
that this interesting Trop-2 mutation didn't affect the protein

174
00:17:38.658 --> 00:17:42.618
expression or its stability, but what it did was shuttle the protein off the

175
00:17:42.638 --> 00:17:46.518
cell surface. Here you can see immunofluorescence confocal microscopy

176
00:17:46.558 --> 00:17:50.428
where wild-type Trop-2 on the tumor cell surface beautifully decorating

177
00:17:50.458 --> 00:17:52.238
the cell membrane. But the

178
00:17:53.378 --> 00:17:57.218
missense mutant Trop-2 entirely internal, and we could show in

179
00:17:57.298 --> 00:18:01.218
models that if you put in wild-type Trop-2, you can convey high sensitivity

180
00:18:01.318 --> 00:18:04.806
to SG. If you put in the mutantThey remain

181
00:18:05.126 --> 00:18:08.706
entirely resistant. So this is a very interesting case,

182
00:18:09.086 --> 00:18:12.466
but of course, when you think about it, the idea that even in an individual patient

183
00:18:12.526 --> 00:18:16.486
you might have resistance based on both the target and the payload is

184
00:18:16.526 --> 00:18:20.446
a cautionary tale for the use of one ADC after another, which might be

185
00:18:20.506 --> 00:18:23.696
related in target or payload. Rachel Abelman

186
00:18:24.066 --> 00:18:27.766
presented this data a couple of years ago at San Antonio

187
00:18:27.786 --> 00:18:31.726
Breast, showing that the time to progression on average

188
00:18:31.766 --> 00:18:35.566
for TNBC patients and patients with HR positive HER2 Negative disease

189
00:18:36.066 --> 00:18:39.806
is substantially shorter on the second ADC, and it

190
00:18:39.846 --> 00:18:42.306
didn't matter which approved ADC you used first.

191
00:18:42.366 --> 00:18:46.086
It didn't matter the sequence or the timing between the

192
00:18:46.146 --> 00:18:49.326
first one and the second one, substantially shorter progression-free

193
00:18:49.426 --> 00:18:53.416
survival. Numbers were small, but this was particularly true

194
00:18:53.766 --> 00:18:57.686
if the second ADC had the same payload, underscoring

195
00:18:57.726 --> 00:19:01.686
an important role for payload-associated resistance in

196
00:19:01.726 --> 00:19:05.566
the setting of progression on SG. We

197
00:19:05.606 --> 00:19:09.386
wanted to look at that more broadly in a case series, and in this

198
00:19:09.466 --> 00:19:12.246
case, through cell-free DNA analysis.

199
00:19:12.306 --> 00:19:16.196
And so we showed in this paper published last year that a number

200
00:19:16.226 --> 00:19:19.706
of patients actually harbored acquired TOP1

201
00:19:19.726 --> 00:19:23.696
mutations. And again, some of them, like R364H, had been previously

202
00:19:23.726 --> 00:19:27.506
described in cell lines as bona fide resistance mutations.

203
00:19:28.306 --> 00:19:31.426
We went on to show that these mutations, by and large, have the

204
00:19:31.486 --> 00:19:34.726
hallmarks of bona fide TOP1 resistance mutations.

205
00:19:34.766 --> 00:19:38.506
This is the crystal structure of TOP1 in blue and DNA in

206
00:19:38.566 --> 00:19:41.306
green. TOP1 engages directly with DNA.

207
00:19:41.686 --> 00:19:45.186
The drug works by intercalating between the protein and the DNA.

208
00:19:45.966 --> 00:19:49.946
The resistance mutations are adjacent to the DNA protein interface, and they

209
00:19:50.006 --> 00:19:53.886
affect that interface so that the protein cannot intercalate.

210
00:19:54.106 --> 00:19:57.446
We then went on to show that indeed, if you track these in the blood by

211
00:19:57.486 --> 00:20:01.306
quantitative ddPCR, that the emergence of these

212
00:20:01.326 --> 00:20:04.486
TOP1 mutations were a harbinger of progression.

213
00:20:06.346 --> 00:20:10.296
So stepping back from this, clearly we need to know at

214
00:20:10.326 --> 00:20:13.366
the level of individual patients what might be the resistance mechanism.

215
00:20:13.426 --> 00:20:16.806
If it's clearly payload dependent, you're going to want to switch payload in your

216
00:20:16.846 --> 00:20:20.146
next ADC. If it's target dependent, conversely, you might want to

217
00:20:20.206 --> 00:20:21.446
switch the target.

218
00:20:23.226 --> 00:20:26.866
So we wanted to look in the lab more broadly at these tumor intrinsic mechanisms.

219
00:20:26.876 --> 00:20:29.106
We've done many CRISPR screens over the years.

220
00:20:29.126 --> 00:20:31.636
This was actually, I think, the first one we've done, probably the most

221
00:20:31.686 --> 00:20:34.626
informative. You can see this is the volcano plot.

222
00:20:34.666 --> 00:20:38.646
Each dot represents a gene. On the left, genes whose knockout sensitizes to SG

223
00:20:38.686 --> 00:20:42.626
and TNBC cells, on the right, those whose knockout induces resistance.

224
00:20:42.686 --> 00:20:46.346
A lot of the players we'd want to see are there, so replication associated repair,

225
00:20:46.426 --> 00:20:50.416
homologous recombination, knockout induced sensitivity, knockout of

226
00:20:50.446 --> 00:20:52.266
TOP1, which is a great positive control.

227
00:20:52.326 --> 00:20:56.256
We know that TOP1 loss, because the drug has to bind to it to work, induces

228
00:20:56.346 --> 00:21:00.126
resistance. From a targeting point of view, the PARP pathway looked quite

229
00:21:00.166 --> 00:21:02.666
intriguing. Loss of PARP1 caused sensitivity.

230
00:21:03.046 --> 00:21:06.566
Conversely, loss of the glycohydrolase PARG that opposes PARP1

231
00:21:07.226 --> 00:21:10.666
induced resistance. And this was not a

232
00:21:10.706 --> 00:21:14.466
surprise. It was known that indeed there's a strong interaction

233
00:21:14.486 --> 00:21:17.886
between PARP inhibition and TOP1 inhibition.

234
00:21:18.546 --> 00:21:22.486
And that is because, as I mentioned, the inhibitor works by intercalating between

235
00:21:22.526 --> 00:21:26.386
TOP1 and DNA, and this complex,

236
00:21:26.486 --> 00:21:30.045
called the TOP1 cleavage complex, where the DNA is cleaved, is

237
00:21:30.186 --> 00:21:33.386
stabilized by the inhibitor and it ultimately breaks down a double-strand break,

238
00:21:33.406 --> 00:21:36.746
leading to cell death. It turns out to clear this, it's a

239
00:21:36.806 --> 00:21:40.686
PARP-dependent pathway where PAR must parlate TDP1, which

240
00:21:40.726 --> 00:21:44.166
is the phosphodiesterase, to cleave the TOP1 off the DNA.

241
00:21:44.506 --> 00:21:46.956
Ubiquitin proteasome pathway then degrades

242
00:21:47.346 --> 00:21:50.776
TOP1. So if you inhibit PARP, you stabilize these

243
00:21:50.806 --> 00:21:54.276
complexes. You have a lot of extra double-strand breaks, and ultimately, death.

244
00:21:54.716 --> 00:21:58.186
So we went on to test clinically, as I'll show you, the PARP pathway.

245
00:21:58.446 --> 00:22:01.236
But also note that there are a number of interesting

246
00:22:01.786 --> 00:22:05.026
players that also mediate this TOP1cc

247
00:22:05.126 --> 00:22:06.936
stabilization if they are inhibited.

248
00:22:07.146 --> 00:22:10.426
Ubiquitin proteasome pathway, which has to degrade TOP1 itself on the

249
00:22:10.446 --> 00:22:14.226
DNA, and then endonucleases that can cleave the DNA to

250
00:22:14.366 --> 00:22:17.286
get rid of this TOP1cc and allow, again,

251
00:22:17.786 --> 00:22:21.306
reassembling of the whole double-stranded DNA.

252
00:22:21.726 --> 00:22:22.006
So

253
00:22:22.846 --> 00:22:26.816
other potential options, including PARP, and we're looking at

254
00:22:26.846 --> 00:22:30.796
those pre-clinically. One of the reasons being that because this

255
00:22:30.806 --> 00:22:34.215
PARP1, TOP1 story had been around for a long time, a number of trials had used

256
00:22:34.226 --> 00:22:36.226
systemic PARP1 and TOP1 inhibitors.

257
00:22:36.926 --> 00:22:40.846
By and large, administered systemically, it's not really tolerable because there's

258
00:22:40.866 --> 00:22:44.146
not a great therapeutic index. A lot of toxicity, particularly to blood

259
00:22:44.186 --> 00:22:47.496
cells, so myelo suppression is a dose-limiting toxicity.

260
00:22:48.306 --> 00:22:52.056
But we hypothesized, and this is work we did with Aditya Bardia, that

261
00:22:52.446 --> 00:22:56.126
the ADC delivery might create a better therapeutic window.

262
00:22:56.176 --> 00:23:00.146
And the hypothesis went like this, that because the ADC delivers higher

263
00:23:00.266 --> 00:23:04.215
doses of the drug to tumor cells than normal cells, that might

264
00:23:04.326 --> 00:23:07.806
create actually a temporal window whereby you could

265
00:23:08.246 --> 00:23:11.806
give the drug, such as SG, and then you could wait.

266
00:23:11.906 --> 00:23:15.466
Normal cells would clear the drug, tumor cells would still have drug still

267
00:23:15.546 --> 00:23:19.396
around, and then come in with a PARP inhibitor and have more effective

268
00:23:19.926 --> 00:23:23.406
and selective effect. We tested this in the laboratory.

269
00:23:23.726 --> 00:23:27.446
If you look in the middle panel, this is in cases where we apply SG, we wash it

270
00:23:27.486 --> 00:23:30.466
out, and then we apply the PARP inhibitor, in this case talazoparib.

271
00:23:31.126 --> 00:23:34.766
And you can see that even though the drugs are not on the cell at the same time,

272
00:23:35.246 --> 00:23:39.166
you actually get synergistic enhancement of

273
00:23:39.206 --> 00:23:42.726
cytotoxicity. And we can see the biochemical hallmark of the

274
00:23:42.786 --> 00:23:46.766
mechanism. As I mentioned, these are cell nuclei here in blue, and the

275
00:23:46.866 --> 00:23:50.526
red is confocal microscopy showing us the stabilized TOP1 cleavage

276
00:23:50.626 --> 00:23:53.426
complex. So when you treat with a drug, you get a stabilized

277
00:23:53.446 --> 00:23:57.350
TOP1cc.Interestingly, once you wash it off, within 30 minutes,

278
00:23:57.390 --> 00:24:01.070
the cell has resolved that, as I showed by all those PARP proteasome

279
00:24:01.110 --> 00:24:04.970
pathways, and eliminated it. But if you put on the PARP inhibitor,

280
00:24:05.270 --> 00:24:08.970
those are stabilized and ultimately leading to double-strand breaks and

281
00:24:09.050 --> 00:24:12.730
cell death. Then together with Aditja, when he was in our

282
00:24:12.790 --> 00:24:16.590
program, now the leader of breast program and translational research at UCLA,

283
00:24:17.230 --> 00:24:21.050
we conducted a Phase 1b2 dose escalation expansion study.

284
00:24:21.830 --> 00:24:25.230
In this case, we started with two cohorts, one a

285
00:24:25.330 --> 00:24:29.290
concurrent dosing, and another one on a staggered dosing schedule

286
00:24:29.330 --> 00:24:33.010
with SG days one and eight, starting the PARP inhibitor on day

287
00:24:33.470 --> 00:24:34.090
15.

288
00:24:35.290 --> 00:24:35.510
And

289
00:24:36.490 --> 00:24:40.330
this slide summarizes some of the data from that trial.

290
00:24:40.370 --> 00:24:43.190
And what we found was that the concurrent

291
00:24:43.250 --> 00:24:46.710
administration was not tolerable from the point of view of

292
00:24:46.750 --> 00:24:50.280
myelosuppression, similar to systemic TOP1/PARP1

293
00:24:50.550 --> 00:24:54.540
administration. You can see that here with greater 71%

294
00:24:54.540 --> 00:24:58.390
dose limiting toxicity and short progression-free survival here in

295
00:24:58.430 --> 00:25:01.550
the swimmers plot. On the other hand, when we dosed

296
00:25:01.630 --> 00:25:02.470
sequentially,

297
00:25:03.610 --> 00:25:06.310
we were able to preserve some level of efficacy.

298
00:25:06.390 --> 00:25:10.380
We have, I think, one patient still on treatment after more than five years,

299
00:25:11.050 --> 00:25:13.720
and no dose-limiting toxicities.

300
00:25:14.450 --> 00:25:18.390
So this is a first step. It was not a randomized trial, so we don't know

301
00:25:18.690 --> 00:25:22.340
clearly about efficacy, but this concept is now going forward in

302
00:25:22.490 --> 00:25:26.450
multiple different versions, and in other diseases

303
00:25:26.530 --> 00:25:30.380
where one of the major advances that may make this even more

304
00:25:30.410 --> 00:25:34.210
exciting as a regimen is the advent of PARP1 selective

305
00:25:34.230 --> 00:25:38.090
inhibitors. The approved PARP1 inhibitors target PARP1 and 2.

306
00:25:38.430 --> 00:25:41.860
Much of the myelosuppression from the combination comes from targeting stem cells,

307
00:25:41.930 --> 00:25:45.710
which primarily express PARP2. So the idea with a

308
00:25:45.730 --> 00:25:49.430
selective PARP1 inhibitor in combination could be more

309
00:25:49.490 --> 00:25:53.210
tolerable, could be tolerable for concurrent dosing,

310
00:25:53.490 --> 00:25:57.430
and allow us to push doses higher, and get efficacy from

311
00:25:57.490 --> 00:26:00.790
this very mechanistically grounded combination.

312
00:26:01.050 --> 00:26:04.530
And that's work going on in the lab, work that's going on in our breast

313
00:26:05.070 --> 00:26:08.799
spore. And we and a lot of folks in the field are still

314
00:26:08.810 --> 00:26:10.710
excited about this combination.

315
00:26:12.010 --> 00:26:15.510
So now let's take a step back and we wanted to look holistically at the

316
00:26:15.530 --> 00:26:18.750
tumors and particularly looking at de

317
00:26:18.870 --> 00:26:22.530
novo resistance pathways. And so we

318
00:26:22.550 --> 00:26:26.190
designed a series of preoperative neoadjuvant trials,

319
00:26:26.550 --> 00:26:30.290
in this case using SG, the first of which led by

320
00:26:30.550 --> 00:26:34.420
Laura Spring, where patients got preoperatively four

