00:39:54.502 --> 00:39:56.862
Ellison's talk, so I will try my best.

557
00:39:58.062 --> 00:40:01.782
Here are my disclosures, none of which are relevant to the talk today.

558
00:40:02.462 --> 00:40:06.162
So I wanted to just briefly introduce bladder cancer to this audience.

559
00:40:06.282 --> 00:40:09.982
I think it's a tumor type that we don't hear that much about

560
00:40:10.042 --> 00:40:12.662
typically at these large meetings.

561
00:40:12.902 --> 00:40:16.562
Eighty-five thousand cases in the US with over half a million

562
00:40:16.882 --> 00:40:20.051
cases in the world. Bladder cancer is a really interesting

563
00:40:20.582 --> 00:40:22.842
tumor because the majority of patients who have

564
00:40:23.702 --> 00:40:27.642
non-muscle invasive bladder cancer have this

565
00:40:27.681 --> 00:40:30.462
superficial growing tumor in their bladders.

566
00:40:30.942 --> 00:40:34.682
But unfortunately, 20% of patients have this muscle-invasive disease that grows

567
00:40:34.962 --> 00:40:37.802
from the inner lining of the bladder and grows radially outward.

568
00:40:38.152 --> 00:40:40.642
And this is the disease that ends up killing patients.

569
00:40:41.502 --> 00:40:44.702
Unfortunately, even patients with localized disease end up

570
00:40:45.962 --> 00:40:49.942
needing a lot of procedures. So it's actually one of the most expensive tumor types

571
00:40:49.982 --> 00:40:53.042
to take care of because they need frequent urologic procedures, including

572
00:40:53.062 --> 00:40:55.402
cystoscopies, as well as radiographic monitoring.

573
00:40:55.972 --> 00:40:59.682
And while we use the term bladder cancer and urothelial carcinoma or

574
00:40:59.782 --> 00:41:03.742
UC fairly synonymously, I think one of the really interesting parts of bladder

575
00:41:03.782 --> 00:41:06.622
cancer is that it's actually a very heterogeneous disease.

576
00:41:06.632 --> 00:41:10.622
And so while the predominant histology that the pathologist sees is

577
00:41:10.682 --> 00:41:14.442
urothelial, there are all these different variant histologies, squamous,

578
00:41:14.472 --> 00:41:17.902
sarcomatoid, plasmacytoid, small cell adenocarcinoma, et cetera,

579
00:41:18.362 --> 00:41:22.342
making the treatment for bladder cancer as a single disease very challenging.

580
00:41:23.282 --> 00:41:26.922
And we aren't quite there at the level that the breast cancer oncologists are.

581
00:41:26.962 --> 00:41:30.582
We don't break up molecular subtypes into HR positive, HR

582
00:41:30.702 --> 00:41:34.382
negative, and HER2 positive. And so we're still a little bit behind in terms of

583
00:41:34.402 --> 00:41:35.422
molecular subtyping.

584
00:41:36.262 --> 00:41:39.242
The final thing that I'll say about bladder cancer is that while the majority of

585
00:41:39.262 --> 00:41:42.902
patients with urothelial carcinoma have lower tract disease that actually

586
00:41:43.022 --> 00:41:46.712
starts, originates in the bladder, about 10 to 15% of patients actually

587
00:41:46.782 --> 00:41:50.528
have urothelial carcinoma that's in the upper tract.So just to remember that

588
00:41:50.618 --> 00:41:53.558
the urothelium actually starts all the way up here in the kidneys, in the renal

589
00:41:53.638 --> 00:41:57.577
pelvis, lines the ureter. And so we extrapolate our

590
00:41:57.618 --> 00:41:58.898
treatments for upper tract

591
00:41:59.858 --> 00:42:03.638
patients from the lower tract regimens, even though we know that while they

592
00:42:03.718 --> 00:42:07.178
share many molecular features, they're actually fairly distinct entities.

593
00:42:08.038 --> 00:42:10.558
So historically, how have we treated bladder cancer?

594
00:42:10.678 --> 00:42:10.898
I think

595
00:42:12.018 --> 00:42:15.918
up until about 10, 15 years ago, we were really using cisplatin, which

596
00:42:15.958 --> 00:42:19.638
of course we know generates DNA damage by binding to the DNA and generating these

597
00:42:19.658 --> 00:42:23.358
bulky adducts. I think over the last 15 years, we've been really

598
00:42:23.418 --> 00:42:26.898
fortunate. Bladder cancer's been a really exciting space, and in particularly

599
00:42:26.958 --> 00:42:30.638
looking at surface protein targeting therapies, which are lab studies, which

600
00:42:30.678 --> 00:42:33.658
include, of course, ADCs, the topic of this session today.

601
00:42:34.118 --> 00:42:37.318
And many of these proteins are still yet undefined in many carcinomas.

602
00:42:37.378 --> 00:42:41.318
And I've been really blown away walking through the posters yesterday

603
00:42:41.338 --> 00:42:45.118
and today, just how many different targets there are, and what Siraj

604
00:42:45.238 --> 00:42:49.058
kind of mentioned in one of his cartoons, like kind of pick what's in the

605
00:42:49.098 --> 00:42:52.638
black box here. And also I think, thinking about the

606
00:42:52.658 --> 00:42:54.378
biomarkers of response and resistance,

607
00:42:55.338 --> 00:42:58.198
which certainly piggybacks off of one of the sessions that Dr.

608
00:42:58.418 --> 00:43:02.378
Pistilli presented yesterday. For those who didn't get to make that talk, it

609
00:43:02.418 --> 00:43:04.578
was really an excellent session. So

610
00:43:05.478 --> 00:43:08.258
not only do we have single-pass transmembrane proteins, which has been the

611
00:43:08.298 --> 00:43:11.798
predominant type of protein that we've been targeting, but we also know that we can

